statement.p:
The matrix A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
defines a matrix transformation T(\xvec) = A\xvec in the following way:
T\left(\twovec{x_1}{x_2}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \twovec{x_1}{x_2} = \cthreevec{3x_1 - 2x_2}{x_1 + 2x_2}{3x_2}.

Suppose we have a function T:\real^3\to\real^2 that
has the form

  T\left(\threevec{x_1}{x_2}{x_3}\right) =
  \begin{bmatrix}
  -4x_1 -x_2 + 2x_3 \\
  x_1 + 2x_2 - x_3 \\
  \end{bmatrix}.

We may write

  \begin{aligned}
  T\left(\threevec{x_1}{x_2}{x_3}\right) 
  \amp {}={}
  \begin{bmatrix}
  -4x_1 -x_2 + 2x_3 \\
  x_1 + 2x_2 - x_3 \\
  \end{bmatrix} \\
  \amp {}={} 
  \twovec{-4x_1}{x_1} + \twovec{-x_2}{2x_2} +
  \twovec{2x_3}{-x_3}  \\
  \amp {}={}
  x_1\twovec{-4}1 + x_2\twovec{-1}2 + x_3\twovec2{-1}  \\
  \amp{}={}
  \begin{bmatrix}
  -4 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
  1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
  \end{bmatrix}
  \threevec{x_1}{x_2}{x_3}.
  \end{aligned}

This shows that T is a matrix transformation
T(\xvec) = A\xvec associated to the matrix
A = 
\begin{bmatrix}
-4 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
\end{bmatrix}.

